NAME
     sass-format

SYNOPSIS
     sass-format [options] [FILES...]

DESCRIPTION
     sass-format is a command-line tool to format .sass files in the mildly idiosyncratic style used at [Unspace](http://unspace.ca). That means:

     1. All property values are placed at an (at least) 30-character left offset.
     2. Unless they start with a `-` (e.g. `left: -30px`) or a `.` (e.g. `@extend .button`), in which case they're shifted left 1 character.

FORMAT EXAMPLE
     #wrapper
       .sidebar
         :border-top               8px solid black
         :margin-right            -100px
       .content
         :width                    500px
         @extend                  .helvetica

ABOUT THE FILES ARGUMENT

     If no flags are provided, FILES should consist of two paths - one input, one output.
     If --stdin is provided, you can specify one path as an output file, or specify none and output will go to stdout.
     If --edit-in-place is provided, all paths are treated as input.
     If --recursive is provided, only the first path is looked at, and it should be a directory.

OPTIONS

    -s, --stdin                      Read input from standard input instead of an input file
    -e, --edit-in-place              Edit files in place. Make sure you've backed them up (preferably using version control).
    -R, --recursive                  Format all the files in a directory. Implies the `-e' flag.
    -o, --offset N                   Specify left character offset for property values (default 30)
